        "question": "Which metal is most reactive among the following?",
        "options": [
          "A. Iron",
          "B. Copper",
          "C. Sodium",
          "D. Gold"
        ],
        "answer": "C. Sodium"
      }
    ],
    "veryShortAnswerQuestions": [
      {
        "question": "What is the reactivity series?",
        "answer": "The arrangement of metals in decreasing order of their reactivity."
      }
    ],
    "didYouKnow": [
      "Gold is so unreactive that it does not tarnish, which is why ancient gold jewelry is still shiny today!"
    ],
    "summary": [
      "Metals are arranged by reactivity; higher metals displace lower ones."
    ],
    "quickRevision": [
      "K > Na > Ca > Mg > Al > Zn > Fe > Pb > H > Cu > Ag > Au"
    ],
    "rememberPoints": [
      "Reactivity -> Displacement -> Extraction Method"
    ]
  },
  "learningOutcomes": [
    "Students will be able to list the reactivity series of metals.",
    "Students will predict displacement reactions based on metal positions.",
    "Students will explain the link between reactivity and extraction methods."
  ],
  "introduction": "Imagine you are a treasure hunter. You find a shiny yellow rock that never rusts (Gold) and a grey rock that turns red when wet (Iron). Why is one so easy to keep and the other so hard? Today, we unlock the secret code of 'Chemical Substances' to understand why metals behave differently!",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "Chemical substances are classified based on their properties. Metals and non-metals differ in how they react with oxygen, water, and acids. The Reactivity Series is a crucial tool that arranges metals by their tendency to lose electrons.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Metals are arranged in the reactivity series from most to least reactive.",
      "A more reactive metal displaces a less reactive metal from its salt solution.",
      "Highly reactive metals (K, Na, Ca) are extracted by electrolysis; less reactive ones by heating."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "The reactivity series is an empirical arrangement of metals. For example, Potassium reacts violently with cold water, while Iron only reacts with steam. This difference determines how we extract them. If a metal is high in the series (like Aluminum), it holds onto oxygen tightly, so we cannot use carbon to remove the oxygen; we must use electricity (Electrolysis). If a metal is low (like Copper or Lead), we can heat its oxide with carbon to get the pure metal. Displacement reactions are the practical application of this series: Zinc + Copper Sulfate -> Zinc Sulfate + Copper."
  }
}
